          "body": "Verses 22-31 are among the most theologically charged in the Old Testament. Wisdom claims pre-creation existence: the LORD *possessed* (or *acquired*, or *created* — *qanah* is disputed) her at the beginning of His way; she was *established from everlasting*; she was *brought forth* (the verb *chul* is the language of birth-pangs) before depths, mountains, hills, earth, and dust existed. Five negative time-markers (*when there were no*, *before*, *before*, *while He had not yet*, *nor*) emphasize that the entire created order came after her. Then verses 27-29 reverse to positive markers: when He *established* the heavens, *inscribed* a circle on the deep, *made firm* the skies, *set* the sea's boundary, *marked out* the foundations — *I was there*. Verse 30 climaxes: she was beside Him as a *master workman* (*amon* — disputed but most likely 'craftsman' or 'artisan'), *daily His delight*, *rejoicing always before Him*. The atmosphere of pre-creation existence is joy. The early church (Athanasius against Arius) wrestled deeply with this passage because the LXX's *ektisen* (*created*) at 8:22 became a weapon for those who said the Son was a created being. The orthodox response was twofold: (1) personified Wisdom is a literary figure, not a metaphysical claim about a created person, and (2) where the New Testament does apply this passage to Christ (Colossians 1:15-17; 1 Corinthians 1:24, 30; John 1:1-3), it carefully preserves His uncreated eternity. The Son is not Wisdom-as-creature; He is the Wisdom of God in whom and by whom all things were made."
